ls; I certainly do.   Looking back, I can say that the private school teachers are more professional in teaching subjects and that they hold students to a higher standard.  None of this &quot;no child left behind&quot;.  The public school system has turned from a process to get soon to be young adults ready for the real world into a fantasy machine that just pumps kids out.  Most teachers in public school systems are too opinionated and a place of learning turns into a brainwashing facility.  Instead of teaching kids how to think, they teach them what to think; and most kids are too young/ignorant to tell the difference.   No there are some very admirable teachers in public schools.  In retrospect, I wish I paid more attention to them.  I respect the teachers that challenge their students and push them to their limits, cause I believe that's one of the best ways one better themselves.  Which is why I prefer the private schools mostly cause the ones I went to didn't make exceptions to the rules.  They taught using one standard of grading and they held the students accountable for their actions (something we're seeing less and less of in the public schools). "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1462" language="en" documentId="3088" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Jester006" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:46PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="1" thumbsDown="0" origId="3088" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1462"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>